(44, 7, 1, 43, 18, 19, 21, 'Are these things so?', 'Inquiry by the High Priest', 'This connection highlights the role of the high priest in questioning both Stephen and Jesus. Both passages feature a high priest asking about teachings and disciples, emphasizing the scrutiny faced by key figures in the early church.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 1, 40, 26, 61, 62, 'Are these things so?', 'High Priest''s Inquiry', 'This connection highlights the role of the high priest in questioning both Stephen and Jesus. Both passages depict a moment where the high priest seeks clarification regarding accusations made against the individuals.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 1, 41, 14, 58, 60, 'Are these things so?', 'High Priest''s Inquiry', 'This connection highlights the role of the high priest in questioning both Stephen and Jesus. Both passages feature a high priest seeking clarification about accusations related to the temple.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 1, 43, 18, 33, 35, 'Are these things so?', 'Authority and Questioning', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning authority. In both passages, figures of authority— the high priest and Pilate— inquire about Jesus, reflecting their roles in the judicial process surrounding him.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 1, 44, 6, 13, 14, NULL, 'Accusations Against Stephen', 'Both passages emphasize the accusations made against Stephen. In Acts 6:13-14, false witnesses claim he spoke blasphemous words, leading to the high priest''s inquiry in Acts 7:1.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 1, 11, 31, 31, 'our father Abraham, when he was in Mesopotamia', 'Abraham''s Journey from Ur', 'This connection highlights Abraham''s movement from Mesopotamia to Haran, as noted in both passages. Acts 7:2 references God''s appearance to Abraham in Mesopotamia, while Genesis 11:31 describes Terah''s journey with Abram from Ur to Haran.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 44, 22, 1, 1, 'Men, brethren, and fathers', 'Addressing the Audience', 'Both passages emphasize a call to attention from the speaker to the audience. The phrase ''Men, brethren, and fathers'' serves as a direct address in both instances, linking the two contexts of defense and proclamation.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 19, 29, 3, 3, 'the God of glory', 'Connection of Divine Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s glory in both passages. Acts 7:2 refers to ''the God of glory,'' while Psalms 29:3 mentions ''the God of glory thundereth,'' emphasizing His majestic presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 16, 9, 7, 7, 'our father Abraham', 'Connection of Abraham''s Calling', 'Both passages emphasize God''s choice of Abraham and his calling from a specific location. Acts 7:2 mentions Abraham''s appearance in Mesopotamia, while Nehemiah 9:7 identifies Ur of the Chaldees as his origin.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 43, 1, 14, 14, 'the God of glory', 'Connection of Divine Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine glory, as both passages reference God''s glory. In Acts, the ''God of glory'' appears to Abraham, while in John, the glory of the Word made flesh is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 58, 1, 3, 3, 'God of glory', 'Connection of Divine Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine glory as both passages reference the concept of glory associated with God. In Acts, the ''God of glory'' appears to Abraham, while Hebrews describes Christ as ''the brightness of his glory.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 2, 1, 15, 7, 7, 'The God of glory appeared unto our father Abraham', 'God''s Call to Abraham', 'This connection highlights God''s direct communication with Abraham in both passages. Acts 7:2 refers to God''s appearance to Abraham, while Genesis 15:7 emphasizes His role in bringing Abraham out of Ur.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 1, 12, 1, 1, 'Get thee out of thy country, and from thy kindred', 'Call of Abram', 'Both passages emphasize God''s command to Abram to leave his country and kindred for a promised land. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s plan as presented in both texts.', 'quotation', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 58, 11, 8, 8, 'Get thee out of thy country', 'Abraham''s Call and Obedience', 'This connection highlights Abraham''s obedience to God''s call to leave his country and kindred. Both passages emphasize the act of going out into an unknown place as a demonstration of faith.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 1, 15, 7, 7, 'Get thee out of thy country', 'Call of Abraham', 'Both passages emphasize God''s directive to Abraham to leave his homeland and journey to a promised land. Acts 7:3 recounts the call to leave, while Genesis 15:7 affirms God''s role in bringing Abraham out of Ur to inherit the land.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 6, 24, 3, 3, 'Get thee out of thy country', 'Call of Abraham', 'This connection highlights God''s call to Abraham to leave his homeland in Acts 7:3, which is echoed in Joshua 24:3 where God recounts leading Abraham from the other side of the flood. Both passages emphasize God''s initiative in guiding Abraham to a new land.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 16, 9, 8, 8, 'come into the land which I shall shew thee', 'Covenant and Promised Land', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s promise to lead His people to a specific land. Both passages emphasize the significance of leaving one''s country and the covenant made regarding the land.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 40, 10, 37, 37, 'Get thee out of thy country', 'Call to Leave Family', 'This connection highlights the theme of prioritizing divine calling over familial ties. Both passages emphasize the necessity of leaving behind family attachments for a greater purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 3, 42, 14, 33, 33, NULL, 'Forsaking for Discipleship', 'This connection highlights the theme of leaving behind one''s previous life to follow God''s call. Both passages emphasize the necessity of forsaking one''s country or possessions to fully commit to discipleship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 4, 1, 12, 4, 5, 'when his father was dead', 'Departure from Haran', 'This connection highlights Abram''s journey from Haran to Canaan. Both passages emphasize his departure after his father''s death and the movement into the land where the audience currently resides.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 4, 1, 11, 31, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Terah and Abram', 'Both passages emphasize Terah''s journey with Abram from Ur of the Chaldees to Haran, highlighting the familial relationship and the transition to the land of Canaan. This connection illustrates the continuity of Abram''s narrative as he moves from his father''s influence to his own calling.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 4, 23, 41, 2, 2, 'land of the Chaldeans', 'Connection of Abraham''s Journey', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s call to a righteous man, as seen in both passages. Acts 7:4 mentions Abraham''s movement from Chaldea, while Isaiah 41:2 refers to a ''righteous man from the east,'' suggesting a link in their journeys and divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 4, 23, 41, 9, 9, NULL, 'Divine Calling and Selection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine selection, as both passages refer to God''s choice of individuals for a specific purpose. In Acts, Abraham is called out of the Chaldeans, while Isaiah speaks of being chosen as God''s servant.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 1, 17, 8, 8, 'to his seed after him', 'Promise of Land to Abraham', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of land to Abraham and his descendants. Acts 7:5 refers to the inheritance promised to Abraham, while Genesis 17:8 explicitly states the land of Canaan as an everlasting possession for his seed.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 1, 12, 7, 7, 'to his seed after him', 'Promise of Land to Seed', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise of land to Abram''s seed. Acts 7:5 refers to the promise of possession, while Genesis 12:7 specifies that the land will be given to his seed.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 2, 6, 7, 8, NULL, 'Promise of Land to Descendants', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of land to Abraham and his descendants. Acts 7:5 mentions the promise to Abraham, while Exodus 6:8 reiterates God''s commitment to give the land to his seed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 5, 2, 5, 5, 'give it to him for a possession', 'Inheritance and Land Promises', 'This connection highlights the theme of land inheritance as both passages discuss God''s promises regarding land ownership. Acts 7:5 mentions a promise of possession, while Deuteronomy 2:5 emphasizes God''s allocation of land to Esau, illustrating the divine distribution of land.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 5, 6, 10, 11, 'give it to him for a possession', 'Promise of Land and Inheritance', 'This connection highlights the promise of land made to Abraham and his descendants. Acts 7:5 refers to the inheritance promised to Abraham, while Deuteronomy 6:10-11 describes the fulfillment of that promise with the Israelites receiving the land.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 16, 9, 8, 8, NULL, 'Covenant and Promised Land', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise of land to Abraham and his descendants. Acts 7:5 highlights the initial promise, while Nehemiah 9:8 confirms the fulfillment of that covenant.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 5, 19, 105, 8, 12, NULL, 'Covenant and Land Promises', 'This connection highlights the promise of land made to Abraham and his descendants. Both passages emphasize God''s commitment to give the land of Canaan as an inheritance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 6, 1, 15, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Prophecy and Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize that Abram''s seed will be strangers in a foreign land and will serve and be afflicted for four hundred years. This connection highlights the prophetic nature of God''s promise to Abram regarding his descendants'' future suffering.', 'prophecy', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 6, 2, 12, 40, 41, 'four hundred years', 'Duration of Israel''s Sojourn', 'This connection highlights the specified duration of Israel''s time in Egypt. Acts 7:6 mentions a period of four hundred years, which is echoed in Exodus 12:40-41, detailing the length of their sojourning.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 6, 48, 3, 17, 17, 'four hundred years', 'Connection of Timeframes in Covenants', 'This connection highlights the significance of the timeframes mentioned in both passages. Acts 7:6 refers to a period of four hundred years, while Galatians 3:17 specifies four hundred and thirty years, emphasizing the continuity and development of God''s covenant promises.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 6, 1, 15, 16, 16, 'sojourn in a strange land', 'Connection of Sojourn and Bondage', 'This connection highlights the theme of sojourning in a strange land and the subsequent return of God''s people. Both passages refer to a period of suffering and eventual deliverance, emphasizing God''s plan for His people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 2, 3, 12, 12, 'serve me in this place', 'Service to God After Deliverance', 'This connection highlights the promise of deliverance from bondage and the subsequent service to God. Both passages emphasize the theme of serving God after being freed from oppression.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 19, 105, 27, 36, 'will I judge, said God', 'Judgment and Deliverance Connection', 'This connection highlights God''s promise to judge the nation in bondage and the subsequent signs and wonders described in Psalms, which demonstrate His power in delivering Israel. Both passages emphasize God''s authority over nations and His commitment to freeing His people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 1, 15, 14, 16, 'will I judge', 'Judgment and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s judgment on the nation that enslaves His people and the subsequent deliverance of those people. The phrases about judgment and coming out after bondage highlight a shared theme of divine intervention and liberation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 2, 7, 1, 14, NULL, 'Judgment and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s judgment on Egypt and the subsequent deliverance of the Israelites. Acts 7:7 mentions God''s judgment on the nation in bondage, which aligns with Exodus 7:1-14''s depiction of God''s actions against Pharaoh to free His people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 16, 9, 9, 11, 'in bondage will I judge, said God', 'Deliverance from Bondage', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s deliverance of His people from bondage. Acts 7:7 speaks of judgment on the nation holding them in bondage, while Nehemiah 9:9-11 recounts God''s actions in delivering Israel from Egypt and their affliction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 19, 74, 12, 14, NULL, 'Divine Judgment and Salvation', 'This connection highlights God''s role in delivering His people from bondage and His power over creation. Both passages emphasize God''s strength in judgment and salvation, as seen in His actions against oppressors and chaotic forces.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 7, 23, 51, 9, 10, 'serve me in this place', 'Deliverance and Judgment Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from bondage and God''s judgment. Both passages emphasize God''s power in leading His people out of oppression and into a place of service.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 1, 17, 9, 14, 'covenant of circumcision', 'Covenant of Circumcision', 'Both passages emphasize the covenant of circumcision given to Abraham and its significance for his descendants. Acts 7:8 references the covenant, while Genesis 17:9-14 details the command for circumcision as a sign of that covenant.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 1, 35, 23, 26, 'Jacob begat the twelve patriarchs', 'Connection of Jacob''s Sons', 'Both passages emphasize the lineage of Jacob through his sons. Acts 7:8 mentions Jacob as a patriarch, while Genesis 35:23-26 lists his sons, highlighting their significance in the covenantal narrative.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 2, 1, 1, 4, 'twelve patriarchs', 'Connection of Patriarchs and Covenant', 'Both passages emphasize the lineage of Jacob and his descendants. Acts 7:8 mentions Jacob and the twelve patriarchs, while Exodus 1:1-4 lists the names of these patriarchs as they enter Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 13, 1, 34, 34, 'Abraham begat Isaac', 'Abraham''s Lineage and Covenant', 'Both passages emphasize Abraham''s role as the patriarch and his direct lineage through Isaac. Acts 7:8 highlights the covenant of circumcision, while 1 Chronicles 1:34 traces the descendants of Abraham through Isaac.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 13, 2, 1, 2, 'the twelve patriarchs', 'Connection of Patriarchs and Covenant', 'This connection highlights the lineage of the patriarchs, linking Abraham''s covenant of circumcision to the twelve sons of Jacob. Both passages emphasize the importance of these foundational figures in Israel''s heritage.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 40, 1, 2, 2, NULL, 'Genealogy of Abraham''s Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize the lineage from Abraham through Isaac and Jacob. This connection highlights the continuity of the patriarchal line leading to the twelve patriarchs and ultimately to Judas.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 8, 43, 7, 22, 22, 'covenant of circumcision', 'Connection of Circumcision in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the practice of circumcision as a significant covenantal act passed down from Abraham through the patriarchs. Both passages emphasize the continuity of this tradition, linking it to the authority of Moses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 9, 1, 39, 2, 2, 'God was with him', 'God''s Presence with Joseph', 'Both passages emphasize that God was with Joseph during his trials. In Acts, it highlights God''s support when Joseph was sold, while Genesis shows God''s presence in his prosperity in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 9, 19, 105, 17, 17, 'sold Joseph into Egypt', 'Joseph''s Betrayal and Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph being sold, highlighting the envy of the patriarchs and God''s purpose in sending him ahead. This connection illustrates the theme of divine providence in the midst of betrayal.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 9, 23, 43, 2, 2, 'God was with him', 'God''s Presence in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize God''s presence during difficult times. In Acts, Joseph is sold into Egypt, yet ''God was with him,'' while Isaiah assures that God will be with those facing overwhelming challenges.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 9, 1, 45, 4, 4, 'sold Joseph into Egypt', 'Joseph''s Betrayal and Reunion', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal, as both passages reference Joseph being sold into Egypt by his brothers. Acts 7:9 mentions the act of selling Joseph, while Genesis 45:4 directly addresses this betrayal when Joseph reveals his identity to his brothers.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 9, 23, 41, 10, 10, 'God was with him', 'God''s Presence in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s presence during difficult times. In Acts, Joseph is sold into Egypt, yet ''God was with him,'' while Isaiah reassures believers that ''I am with thee'' in their fears.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 9, 40, 27, 18, 18, 'moved with envy', 'Envy Leading to Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of envy leading to betrayal in both passages. In Acts, Joseph is sold due to the envy of the patriarchs, while in Matthew, Jesus is delivered out of envy.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 20, 3, 4, 4, 'favour and wisdom in the sight', 'Favor and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of finding favor and wisdom in the sight of others. Both passages emphasize the importance of divine favor leading to success and good standing with people.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 55, 4, 18, 18, 'delivered him out of all his afflictions', 'Divine Deliverance and Preservation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine deliverance in both passages. Acts 7:10 speaks of God delivering Joseph from afflictions, while 2 Timothy 4:18 expresses confidence in the Lord''s deliverance from evil works.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 1, 48, 16, 16, 'delivered him out of all his afflictions', 'Divine Favor and Redemption', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention and favor, as seen in both passages. In Acts, Joseph is delivered and given favor, while in Genesis, the Angel redeems Jacob, suggesting a continuity of God''s protective role.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 20, 2, 6, 6, 'wisdom in the sight of Pharaoh', 'Wisdom and Favor from God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of wisdom given by God. In Acts, wisdom is granted to Joseph, while Proverbs states that the Lord gives wisdom, highlighting the divine source of understanding.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 19, 22, 24, 24, 'afflictions', 'Affliction and Divine Favor', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in times of affliction. Both passages emphasize how God responds to the cries of the afflicted, providing favor and wisdom in their distress.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 1, 42, 6, 6, 'governor over Egypt', 'Joseph''s Governance in Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph''s role as governor over Egypt. Acts 7:10 highlights his elevation by Pharaoh, while Genesis 42:6 describes him as the governor who sold grain to the people.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 10, 19, 34, 17, 19, NULL, 'Divine Deliverance in Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in delivering individuals from their troubles and afflictions. Acts 7:10 highlights Joseph''s deliverance from afflictions, while Psalms 34:17-19 speaks of the Lord delivering the righteous from their troubles.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 11, 1, 41, 54, 57, 'found no sustenance', 'Famine and Sustenance Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of famine and the search for sustenance. Both passages describe a severe dearth affecting the land, leading people to seek help from Joseph in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 11, 1, 42, 5, 5, 'great affliction: and our fathers found no sustenance', 'Connection of Famine and Sustenance', 'Both passages emphasize the famine affecting the land, leading to a search for sustenance. Acts 7:11 refers to a dearth in Egypt and Canaan, while Genesis 42:5 describes the sons of Israel coming to buy corn due to the famine.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 11, 1, 43, 1, 1, 'dearth over all the land', 'Connection of Famine References', 'Both passages emphasize the severity of famine affecting the land. Acts 7:11 mentions a dearth, while Genesis 43:1 states the famine was sore, highlighting the dire circumstances faced by the people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 11, 1, 45, 5, 6, 'great affliction: and our fathers found no sustenance', 'Famine and Preservation of Life', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of famine affecting the land, leading to a lack of sustenance. Acts 7:11 mentions a dearth in Egypt and Chanaan, while Genesis 45:5-6 discusses a famine in the land that God used to preserve life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 11, 19, 105, 16, 16, 'great affliction', 'Connection of Famine and Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize a famine affecting the land, leading to great affliction and lack of sustenance. This connection highlights the severity of the famine as a divine act impacting the people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 12, 1, 42, 1, 24, 'there was corn in Egypt', 'Famine and Provision in Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize the need for corn in Egypt during a famine. Jacob''s directive to send his sons to buy corn connects directly to the narrative of their journey to Egypt for sustenance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 12, 1, 43, 2, 2, 'corn in Egypt', 'Food Supply in Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize the need for food, with Jacob sending his sons to Egypt for corn. This connection highlights the urgency of their situation and the reliance on Egypt for sustenance.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 13, 1, 45, 1, 18, 'Joseph was made known to his brethren', 'Joseph Reveals Himself', 'This connection highlights the moment Joseph reveals his identity to his brothers, as noted in both passages. Acts 7:13 summarizes this significant event, emphasizing the recognition of Joseph by his brethren.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 1, 46, 26, 27, 'threescore and fifteen souls', 'Connection of Family Counts', 'Both passages emphasize the count of souls associated with Jacob''s family entering Egypt. Acts 7:14 states ''threescore and fifteen souls,'' while Genesis 46:26-27 refers to ''threescore and ten'' souls, highlighting a numerical connection in the context of Jacob''s lineage.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 5, 10, 22, 22, NULL, 'Connection of Family Numbers', 'Both passages emphasize the number of persons who went down into Egypt, specifically mentioning ''threescore and ten'' or ''threescore and fifteen'' souls. This connection highlights the continuity of the Israelite family''s journey and growth.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 2, 1, 5, 5, 'threescore and fifteen souls', 'Connection of Joseph and Jacob''s Family', 'Both passages emphasize the number of souls associated with Jacob''s family. Acts 7:14 mentions ''threescore and fifteen souls,'' while Exodus 1:5 states ''seventy souls,'' highlighting the continuity of the family lineage.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 1, 45, 9, 11, 'called his father Jacob to him', 'Joseph''s Call to Jacob', 'Both passages emphasize Joseph''s invitation to Jacob and his family to come to Egypt. Acts 7:14 references the gathering of Jacob and his kindred, while Genesis 45:9-11 details Joseph''s command to bring them to him during the famine.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 13, 2, 5, 6, 'all his kindred', 'Connection of Family Lineage', 'This connection highlights the theme of family lineage, as both passages reference the descendants of Jacob and his sons. Acts 7:14 mentions Jacob''s kindred, while 1 Chronicles 2:5-6 lists the sons of Judah, emphasizing the importance of genealogy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 14, 19, 105, 23, 23, 'his father Jacob to him', 'Joseph''s Family in Egypt', 'This connection highlights the arrival of Jacob and his family in Egypt, as mentioned in both passages. Acts 7:14 refers to Joseph calling his father Jacob and his kindred, while Psalms 105:23 notes Israel''s (Jacob''s) sojourn in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 15, 1, 49, 33, 33, 'he, and our fathers', 'Jacob''s Death and Burial', 'This connection highlights the moment of Jacob''s death in both passages. Acts 7:15 refers to Jacob''s death in Egypt, while Genesis 49:33 describes the circumstances of his passing and being gathered to his people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
